if(s)return"Best ways to build your vocabulary:\n\n\ud83d\udcd6 1. Learn words IN CONTEXT \u2014 not isolated lists\nRead articles, watch shows, listen to podcasts\n\n\ud83d\uddc2\ufe0f 2. Use SPACED REPETITION\nReview new words after 1 day, 3 days, 1 week, 1 month\n\n\ud83d\udd17 3. Learn word FAMILIES\nfriend \u2192 friendly \u2192 friendship \u2192 unfriendly \u2192 befriend\n\n\ud83d\udd8a\ufe0f 4. WRITE sentences using new words immediately\n\n\ud83c\udfaf 5. Aim for 10\u201315 new words per day\n\n\ud83d\udcf1 6. Label objects around your home in English\n\n\ud83d\udcac 7. USE words in conversation \u2014 that's how they stick!\n\nFocus on high-frequency words first (the most common 2,000 words cover 95% of everyday English) \u2728"
s=B.d.n(o,"reading")
if(!s)r=B.d.n(o,"improve")&&B.d.n(o,"read")
else r=!0
if(r)return"How to improve your English reading:\n\n\ud83d\udcda Start at YOUR level \u2014 don't struggle with texts that are too hard\n\n\ud83c\udfaf Active reading strategies:\n1. Preview headings before you read\n2. Guess meaning from context before using a dictionary\n3. Read the same text TWICE \u2014 first for general meaning, then for details\n\n\ud83d\udcf0 Best materials by level:\nA1-A2: Graded readers, simple news (BBC Learning English)\nB1-B2: Real news articles, short stories\nC1-C2: Novels, academic articles, opinion pieces\n\n\u23f0 Habit: Read 15\u201320 minutes EVERY DAY\nConsistency beats long sessions once a week!\n\n\ud83d\udd11 Focus on: text structure, main idea, supporting details, writer's purpose \ud83d\udcd6"
if(!B.d.n(o,"writing"))r=B.d.n(o,"improve")&&B.d.n(o,"writ")
else r=!0
if(r)return"How to improve your English writing:\n\n\ud83d\udcdd Key principles:\n1. Plan before you write \u2014 outline your main points\n2. One idea per paragraph\n3. Use topic sentences to start each paragraph\n4. Connect ideas with linking words:\n   Adding: furthermore, in addition, moreover\n   Contrasting: however, although, on the other hand\n   Concluding: therefore, as a result, consequently\n\n\u270d\ufe0f Practice ideas:\n\u2022 Keep a daily journal in English\n\u2022 Write emails or messages in English\n\u2022 Summarise articles you read\n\u2022 Use the Writing Practice section in this app!\n\n\ud83d\udd0d Always proofread:\nCheck: spelling, punctuation, subject-verb agreement, tenses\n\n\ud83d\udca1 Quality > Quantity \u2014 one well-written paragraph is better than three rushed ones \ud83d\udcc4"
if(B.d.n(o,"speaking")||B.d.n(o,"accent")||B.d.n(o,"pronunciation")||B.d.n(o,"fluency"))return'How to improve your English speaking:\n\n\ud83d\udde3\ufe0f Fluency tips:\n1. Think in English \u2014 don\'t translate from your first language\n2. Speak DAILY \u2014 even to yourself (self-talk practice!)\n3. Use filler phrases: "Let me think...", "That\'s a good point..."\n4. Don\'t stop to correct every mistake \u2014 flow matters more\n\n\ud83c\udfaf Pronunciation:\n\u2022 Listen and repeat (shadowing technique)\n\u2022 Record yourself and compare to native speakers\n\u2022 Focus on word stress \u2014 EnGLISH, not ENglish\n\u2022 Learn the 44 English phoneme sounds\n\n\ud83d\udcfa Resources:\nYouTube: BBC Learning English, English with Lucy\nPodcasts: 6 Minute English (BBC)\n\n\ud83c\udfa4 Use the Speaking Practice section in this app to practise and get feedback! \ud83d\udcac'
if(B.d.n(o,"listen")||B.d.n(o,"listening"))return'How to improve your English listening:\n\n\ud83d\udc42 Why it\'s hard: native speakers speak fast, use contractions, and reduce sounds ("going to" \u2192 "gonna")\n\n\ud83d\udcfb Practice strategies:\n1. Listen ACTIVELY \u2014 take notes, predict what comes next\n2. Watch with subtitles \u2192 then without\n3. Listen to the same clip multiple times\n4. Expose yourself to DIFFERENT accents (British, American, Australian)\n\n\ud83c\udfa7 Best resources:\n\u2022 BBC Learning English (bbc.co.uk/learningenglish)\n\u2022 TED Talks (with transcripts!)\n\u2022 Podcasts: 6 Minute English, The English We Speak\n\u2022 YouTube: Real English channels\n\n\u23f0 Daily habit: 15 minutes of focused listening + 30+ minutes of passive listening (background)\n\n\ud83d\udca1 Use the Listening section in this app \u2014 it has British, American, Australian and more accents! \ud83c\udf0d'
if(!B.d.n(o,"correct"))r=B.d.n(o,"grammar")&&B.d.n(o,"check")
else r=!0
if(r){if(B.d.n(o,"don't like")&&B.d.n(o,"she"))return"I can see the error:\n\n\u274c \"She don't like apples\"\n\u2705 \"She doesn't like apples\"\n\nRule: With he/she/it in the present simple, use DOESN'T (not don't):\n\u2022 I don't / You don't / We don't / They don't\n\u2022 He DOESN'T / She DOESN'T / It DOESN'T\n\nMore examples:\n\u2705 \"He doesn't work on weekends.\"\n\u2705 \"She doesn't know the answer.\"\n\u2705 \"It doesn't matter.\" \ud83d\ude0a"
return'To correct your sentence, please type it in the chat and I\'ll identify any errors and explain the rules.\n\nCommon grammar areas to check:\n\u2022 Subject-verb agreement (he/she/it + s)\n\u2022 Tense consistency\n\u2022 Article usage (a/an/the)\n\u2022 Prepositions (in/on/at)\n\u2022 Word order\n\u2022 Singular vs plural nouns\n\nJust type: "Please correct: [your sentence]" \ud83d\udcdd'}if(B.d.n(o,"idiom")||B.d.n(o,"business english"))return'5 Essential Business English Idioms:\n\n\ud83d\udcbc 1. "Think outside the box"\n= be creative, find unusual solutions\n"We need to think outside the box on this project."\n\n\ud83e\udd1d 2. "Touch base"\n= make contact, check in with someone\n"Let\'s touch base next week to discuss progress."\n\n\ud83d\udcca 3. "Get the ball rolling"\n= start something, begin a process\n"Who wants to get the ball rolling on the new campaign?"\n\n\u23f0 4. "On the same page"\n= in agreement, have the same understanding\n"Before we proceed, let\'s make sure we\'re all on the same page."\n\n\ud83c\udfaf 5. "Hit the ground running"\n= start something quickly and with energy\n"We need someone who can hit the ground running from day one." \ud83d\ude80'
if(B.d.n(o,"common mistake")||B.d.n(o,"typical mistake"))return'Top 10 Common English Mistakes:\n\n1. \u274c "I am agree" \u2192 \u2705 "I agree"\n2. \u274c "She don\'t like" \u2192 \u2705 "She doesn\'t like"\n3. \u274c "Peoples" \u2192 \u2705 "People" (no plural s)\n4. \u274c "Informations" \u2192 \u2705 "Information" (uncountable)\n5. \u274c "I am boring" \u2192 \u2705 "I am bored" (feeling vs causing)\n6. \u274c "More better" \u2192 \u2705 "Better"\n7. \u274c "Since 3 years" \u2192 \u2705 "For 3 years"\n8. \u274c "I have 25 years" \u2192 \u2705 "I am 25 years old"\n9. \u274c "She explained me" \u2192 \u2705 "She explained to me"\n10. \u274c "According to my opinion" \u2192 \u2705 "In my opinion"\n\nDo any of these apply to you? \ud83d\ude0a'
if(B.d.n(o,"plan")&&s)return"Reading Improvement Plan \u2014 4 weeks:\n\n\ud83d\udcc5 Week 1: Foundation\n\u2022 Read 1 short article daily (BBC Learning English)\n\u2022 Note 5 new words each day\n\u2022 Use the Reading section in this app (A2-B1 level)\n\n\ud83d\udcc5 Week 2: Speed\n\u2022 Increase to 2 articles per day\n\u2022 Time yourself \u2014 aim to improve pace\n\u2022 Practice skimming for main ideas\n\n\ud83d\udcc5 Week 3: Depth\n\u2022 Read 1 longer text weekly (500+ words)\n\u2022 Summarise each text in 3 sentences\n\u2022 Focus on text structure and argument\n\n\ud83d\udcc5 Week 4: Challenge\n\u2022 Read authentic English content (news, blogs)\n\u2022 Answer comprehension questions (use the app!)\n\u2022 Review all vocabulary from the month\n\n\ud83c\udfaf Goal: Read EVERY DAY \u2014 even 15 minutes makes a huge difference over 4 weeks! \ud83d\udcd6"
